When a small group of living beings (a small population) separates from the main and original group (e.g. by crossing a mountain range or river, or migrating to a new island and can not return) they will often find themselves in a different environment than they had before.
This new environment has different resources and competitors, so that the new population will need characteristics or adaptations different from those it needed before to be a strong competitor.
The original population has not changed anything or anything; they still need the same adaptations as before.
Over time, as the new population begins to adapt to its new environment, it becomes less and less like the other population.
Finally, after thousands or even millions of years, the two populations were so different, so different that they could no longer be considered the same species.
This process is called speciation, which means the formation of new species, which is a consequence that cannot be avoided and a very important part of evolution.
